'''Urban Engines''' is a data analytics [[startup company|startup]] based in [[Silicon Valley]], [http://blog.urbanengines.com acquired by Google in September 2016], that uses data to give insight into cities and how people move around in them.<ref name=Computerworld>{{cite web|title=Computerworld|url=http://www.computerworld.com/article/2882732/urban-engines-using-data-to-power-a-better-commute.html|publisher=Computerworld|accessdate=10 December 2015}}</ref> Founder and CEO Shiva Shivakumar says the company is mapping the “Internet of Moving Things,” as quoted by the New York Times, which is a new way of mapping objects in motion.<ref name=TheNewYorkTimes>{{cite web|title=The New York Times|url=http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/02/10/a-new-mobile-map-captures-internet-of-moving-things/|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=10 December 2015}}</ref> The company’s goal is to improve mobility in cities.<ref name=JacksonvilleBizJournal>{{cite web|title=Jacksonville Business Journal|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/jacksonville/news/2015/06/10/new-transit-app-has-goals-even-bigger-than-helping.html|publisher=Jacksonville Business Journal|accessdate=10 December 2015}}</ref>

Urban Engines has developed a new type of database, which maps objects in motion, called a “Space/Time Engine”,<ref name="TheNewYorkTimes"/> and currently has deals with cities like, Washington D.C., São Paulo and Singapore<ref name=Recode>{{cite web|title=Recode|url=http://recode.net/2014/05/15/google-backed-startup-develops-mobile-games-to-ease-urban-congestion/|publisher=Vox Media|accessdate=10 December 2015}}</ref> as well as delivery and [[logistics]] companies.<ref name="Computerworld"/>

The company also released a commuter app with “mixed-mode routing,”<ref name=TechCrunch1>{{cite web|title=TechCrunch|url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/06/09/urban-engines-wants-to-help-you-leverage-all-forms-of-transit/#.jgndsu:C80R|publisher=TechCrunch|accessdate=10 December 2015}}</ref> which evaluates different modes of transportation – walking, driving, public transit, and Uber – to give users the quickest routes.<ref name="TechCrunch1"/> The app is built on Urban Engines own proprietary mapping system.<ref name="JacksonvilleBizJournal"/>

==History and funding==
The company was founded by Shiva Shivakumar and Balaji Prabhakar. Shiva was previously VP of Engineering and a Distinguished Entrepreneur at [[Google]] (2001-2010), who helped build [[AdSense|Adsense]], Search Appliances and Cloud Apps, and Balaji is a Stanford professor and director of the Stanford Center for Societal Networks, a prominent research initiative to make societal networks smarter, more scalable and more efficient.<ref name=TechCrunch2>{{cite web|title=TechCrunch|url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/05/15/backed-by-google-ventures-and-eric-schmidt-urban-engines-wants-to-solve-urban-congestion-using-data-intelligence/|publisher=TechCrunch|accessdate=10 December 2015}}</ref>

Urban Engines has raised an undisclosed amount of money led by Google Ventures. Andreessen Horowitz, SV Angel, Greylock, Samsung Ventures, early Google investor Ram Shriram and Google Chairman Eric Schmidt also participated.<ref name="Recode"/>

