A w'''elding blanket''' is a piece of [[safety equipment]] designed to protect equipment and the [[welder]] while [[welding]].<ref>{{Cite web| last = Harbor Freight Tools| title = Fiberglass Welding Blanket| work = Harbor Freight Tools| accessdate = 2015-05-29| url = http://www.harborfreight.com/6-ft-x-8-ft-fiberglass-welding-blanket-95015.html}}</ref> A welding blanket typically consists of a layer of flexible protective material containing unexpanded [[vermiculite]] and inorganic heat resistant fibrous material. When contacted by spatter of molten metal during a welding process the material protects the surrounding areas by maintaining the structural integrity of the blanket.<ref>{{Cite| last1 = Skinner| first1 = Mark C.| last2 = Schwartz| first2 = Thomas W.| title = Welding blanket| accessdate = 2015-05-29| date = 1989-07-18| url = http://www.google.com/patents/US4849273}}</ref> Many modern welding blankets are made of flame retardant [[fiberglass]] and can stand working temperatures ranging from 300 to 2,500 degrees Fahrenheit. Historically welding blankets were made of woven [[asbestos]], however due to safety concerns have been widely discontinued.<ref>{{Cite web| last = Sokolove Law| title = Asbestos in Welding Blankets -| work = Asbestos.net| accessdate = 2015-05-29| url = http://www.asbestos.net/exposure/products/general/welding-blankets/}}</ref>
